      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Sides of Tipper Gore</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Mary Fenzel objects to effort, in May 19 profile, to categorize Tipper Gore as traditional or elusive; says she is woman empowered with individuality, passion and loyalty</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 19 front-page article portrays Tipper Gore as someone who seeks privacy. Yet she is also said to be a woman who humbly joins with other mothers against gun violence, seeks out the homeless at night and speaks to parents of gays (and, indeed, all parents) about the need for unconditional love.</p>
        <p>Is Mrs. Gore a woman who retreats from public scrutiny or, in fact, a woman who embodies the struggles so many women face today: balancing work, promoting social justice and, most important, caring for their families?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 19 front-page article portrays Tipper Gore as someone who seeks privacy. Yet she is also said to be a woman who humbly joins with other mothers against gun violence, seeks out the homeless at night and speaks to parents of gays (and, indeed, all parents) about the need for unconditional love.</p>
        <p>Is Mrs. Gore a woman who retreats from public scrutiny or, in fact, a woman who embodies the struggles so many women face today: balancing work, promoting social justice and, most important, caring for their families?</p>
        <p>Must we categorize Mrs. Gore as traditional or elusive, or can we appreciate her as a woman empowered with individuality, passion and loyalty?</p>
        <p>MARY  FENZEL  Ridgewood, N.J., May 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
